Exploratory Data Analysis using Python - A Case Study¶

Analyzing the Netflix Original Films & IMDB Scores Dataset¶

A basic exploratory data analysis on a small dataset as a part of the Jovian's Data Analysis with Python: Zero to Pandas course.

The aim of this project is to get familiarized with the concepts of data analytics with the help of python libraries such as pandas, numpy, matplotlib and seaborn.

Performing Exploratory Analysis And Visualizations¶

Computing some statistics on the data and taking notes on some interesting insights

Now let's see the IMDB scores of these films with the help of a histogram.

Histogram is a graph showing the frequency distribution and often used for numeric data

In [11]:
plt.title("IMDB Scores Distribution") #setting the title of the plot

This histogram shows us that most of the films' IMDB score lie between around 6.3-7.1

Let's see how many different types genres of the films we have got using a bar chart

Bar Chart displays data using rectangular bars. One axis of a bar chart measures a value, while the other axis lists variables

Asking And Answering Questions About The Data¶

Let's ask some interesting questions about our data and how we can solve it using the concepts of pandas, matplotlib and seaborn.

Question 1:¶

Which movie genres have been the most loved over the years?

We need to answer how the genres have changed over the years and which genres have been the most loved over the years by analyzing their IMDB scores.

Let's analyze the genres of the movies over the year using a line plot.

Line Plot is a way to display data along a number line

Since there are about 100+ different genres, we'll only analyze a few of the common genres which have a film count of greater than 5

In [17]:
# filtering out the genres which have a film count greater than 5

genre_filter=df.groupby('Genre').filter(lambda x : len(x)>5).sort_values(by="Release Year")
#the filter() method subsets the dataframe rows or columns according to the specified index labels.

# plotting the genre_filter in a line plot along with the years 
g=sns.lineplot(data=genre_filter, x=genre_filter["Release Year"], y=genre_filter['IMDB Score'], hue=genre_filter["Genre"], ci=None,linewidth = 2, palette="Set2")
g.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.35, 1), prop={'size': 15})
fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(12, 8)

The timeline graph shows the IMDB scores of each genre over the years. The top 3 genres with highest IMDB Scores are Concert Film, Crime drama and Documentary.

Let's see the number of films of these 3 genres have using a pie chart.

Pie Chart represents the data in a circular graph. The entire “pie” represents 100 percent of a whole, while the pie “slices” represent portions of the whole

In [19]:
#storing the top 3 genres with highest IMDB scores in a list
list_of_genre= ["Documentary", "Crime drama", "Concert Film"] 

genre_list_count=[]
for i in range(0,3):
    genre_count=len(df[df['Genre'] == list_of_genre[i]])

    genre_list_count.append(genre_count) # appending the total count of each genre in the list

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_axes([0,0,1,1])
ax.axis('equal')
colorss = ['#FEA82F','#1BE7FF','#A599B5']
ax.pie(genre_list_count, labels = list_of_genre,autopct='%1.2f%%', colors=colorss, wedgeprops = {'linewidth': 3}, radius=1.2, textprops = {"fontsize":15})
plt.show()

We can see from this pie chart that about 90% of our films are of the documentary genre and is one of the most loved films over the years.

Question 2¶

Does the type of movies depend on their release month or not?

Let's try to answer whether the type or genre of the films changed depending on the month of their release like were the Christmas movies mostly released during the month of December when Christmas is near or maybe patriotic films were usually released during the month of independence day

We will analyze the months of the movies related to America's common public holidays and celebrations such as Christmas, Halloween, Veteran's Day, Easter and others.

In [20]:
# filtering out the genres related to these holidays

# analyzing the 'horror' genre
genre_horror=df[(df["Genre"] == "Horror")]
genre_horror_count=genre_horror.groupby("Release Month")["Release Month"].count().nlargest(12)

y=genre_horror_count
x=y.index

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
l=sns.barplot(x=x,y=y);
l.set(title='Distribution of Horror Films and their Release Month ', xlabel="", ylabel="Count");

From this visualization we can see that most of the horror films were released during the month of October since it's the month of Halloween.

Next we'll try to observe Christmas movies. Since there is no specific genre for 'Christmas', we will filter out the movies using the 'Title' column which will contain the string 'Christmas'

In [21]:
#filtering out the dataframe 

# Christmas movies
christmas_movies=df[df['Title'].str.contains("Christmas", case=False)]

#plotting the bar chart
christmas_count=christmas_movies.groupby("Release Month")["Release Month"].count().nlargest(12)

y=christmas_count
x=y.index

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
l=sns.barplot(x=x,y=y);
l.set(title='Distribution of Christmas Films and their Release Month ', xlabel="", ylabel="Count");

Here we can see that all the Christmas movies ever released were either in the month of November and December since these months are near Christmas.

Lastly, let's observe the release months of romance movies

In [22]:
romance_movies= df[df["Genre"].str.contains("Romance|Romantic", case=False) ]
romance_movies

#plotting bar chart
romance_count=romance_movies.groupby("Release Month")["Release Month"].count().nlargest(12)

y=romance_count
x=y.index

fig=plt.figure(figsize=(15,7))
l=sns.barplot(x=x,y=y);
l.set(title='Distribution of Christmas Films and their Release Month ', xlabel="", ylabel="Count");

The highest count of Romance movies were released in February since Valentine's Day is in this month.

From these visualizations, we can see that this could be a marketing tactic by the Netflix to release these films during the month of these respective celebrations to grasp the attention of the audience.

Question 3¶

How much are Animated/Anime Movies loved over the years

Now, we'll try to see how much of these anime and animated movies have been loved by the audience by analyzing their IMDB Scores and should Netflix release more animated films.

In [23]:
# filtering out animated/anime movies

genre_animated=df[df['Genre'].str.contains("anime|animation", case=False)].sort_values(by="Release Year")

x=genre_animated["Release Year"]
y=genre_animated['IMDB Score']

# plotting the genre_filter in a line plot along with the years 
g=plt.plot(x, y )
plt.title("IMDB Scores of Animated Movies over the Years")
fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(22, 8)

From this graph, we can see that animated movies have been doing quite well till 2019 but then there's a sudden drop but this drop could be caused by an outlier maybe. So overall, animated movies did pretty well so Netflix should continue to release more animated films.

Question 4¶

How good did movies with language other than English did?

Lastly, we will try to analyze that did non-English language movies good and should Netflix continue to release these films.

In [26]:
# plotting the non-english films in a line plot along with the years 
non_eng_movies=df[df["Language"].str.contains("English")==False]
non_eng=non_eng_movies.groupby('Language').filter(lambda x : len(x)>5).sort_values(by="Release Year")

non_eng_graph=sns.lineplot(data=non_eng, x=non_eng["Release Year"], y=non_eng['IMDB Score'], hue=non_eng["Language"], ci=None,linewidth = 2, palette="Set2")
non_eng_graph.legend(loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(1.35, 1), prop={'size': 15}, title="Language")
non_eng_graph.set(title="IMDB Scores of Non-English Films over the Years")

fig = plt.gcf()
fig.set_size_inches(12, 8)

It seems like most of the non-English films have only a little bit of ups and downs based on their IMDB Scores but we can see a drastic fall in Italian and Indonesian movies so these 2 are not doing well for Netflix.

The films the most best are Spanish, Japanese and Portuguese films so it would be good for Netflix to continue releasing these films.

Conclusion¶

This is the end of our exploratory analysis on the Netflix dataset. The main intention of this analysis was to get familiar with basic concepts of data analytics and visualization, how to ask and answer data-driven questions and to get a good grasp on python pandas, numpy, matplotlib and seaborn.

Some quite interesting insights were noted above along with visualizations. There are still so many more questions yet to be answered about this data but only a few have been answered for now to keep it brief.
